bug.short_desc: Asus B150M-A D3 mainboard: sddm segfaults when booting from KDE installation media
bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

long_desc.thetext:
I tried installing from Fedora 24 beta media (using dis on key). Had success with the Gnome based installation: Fedora-Workstation-Live-x86_64-24_Beta Failed with KDE installations: Fedora-KDE-Live-i386-24_Beta Fedora-KDE-Live-x86_64-24_Beta Fedora-Jam_KDE-Live-x86_64-24_Beta
I remove the "quiet" option when booting, only then I can see that the problem is a segmentation fault in sddm.
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): Fedora 14-beta installation
How reproducible: = always
Steps to Reproduce: 1.Create installation media (copy image to disk on key) 2.Insert media into computer; Reboot form usb disk. 3.(optional, remove the "quiet" option from the boot options) 4.Continue boot and wait.
Actual results: Cannot install KDE based Fedora 24-beta (cannot reach the graphical installation screen)
Expected results: I would like to be able to install KDE based Fedora 24.
Additional info: This is probably hardware related. Intel Skylake/HD Graphics 530.
See also: Bug 1329715

The referenced bug #1329715 was specific to 32bit/i686 (not relevant here)
Can you give details about what video hardware and/or driver gets used here? (It's most likely an issue of opengl support not functioning properly)

Thanks Rex Dieter. I have reinstalled from Fedora-Workstation-Live-x86_64-24_Beta. Attached outputs from lscpu, lspci -v and from glxinfo.
Then I installed all the requirements and compiled and tried FreeCAD from the github sources. AFAIK FreeCAD requires opengl. It's compiled and running OK.

OK, appears to be intel hardware.
Now, if you can provide a backtrace or abrt-report for the crashes, that would help our debugging greatly. (Otherwise, it's just speculation)

Suggestions how to do that?
Options are very limited when running from the installation media. Could I just install sddm on the workstation (gnome) installation and run it from a console (after "init 3")?

the abrt applet should be present on both kde and gnome/workstation spins, it should notify of system crashes.
That said, yes, you can install sddm on top of workstation (as root):
dnf install sddm
systemctl enable sddm --force and reboot (for subsequent boots)
or to start only this time: systemctl stop gdm (or whatever your current non-sddm DM is) systemctl start sddm
I can confirm that this problem is fixed in the final release of Fedora 24 KDE. Therefore I'm closing this bug.
